Enters the English language in 1897 (in translation from Richard Krafft-Ebing (c.1886) and Magnus Hirschfeld (c.1890s)).

Originating in medical discourse, the term invert refers to people who are attracted to others of the same sex.  Inversion was considered congenital. It offered the political advantages that accrue to the nature side of the nature/nurture debate about the origins of sexual orientation.

Now outdated/offensive. 